                   Installing O64ml on a Linux machine
                   ===================================

PREREQUISITES
=============

* The Bash shell, and some standard commands the configuration script will
  check for their availability.


* The OCaml LTS (Long Term Support) release 4.14.x (NOT OCaml >= 5.x)
      ^^^^^^^^^                             ^^^^^^

  If not installed:

  see <https://ocaml.org/install> for info about OCaml installation; also
  see <https://ocaml.org/docs/install-a-specific-ocaml-compiler-version>.

  This guide assumes that your OCaml installation is managed by Opam, the
  OCaml Package Manager.


* The OByteLib package
      ^^^^^^^^

  If not installed:

  - Select the right Opam switch if necessary:

	opam switch the_switch_where_you_installed_ocaml_4.14.x

  - Install OByteLib:

	opam update
	opam install obytelib


* The ACME crossassembler, release 0.97 ("Zem"), 16 Nov 2025 or newer
      ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^                        ^^^^^^^^^^^

  You can check your installed version, if any, with

	acme --version

  If it's not installed on your system or it's an obsolete version, the O64ml
  configuration script will propose to compile and install a suitable release
  for you; or, if you prefer, you can manually download and install it from
  <https://sourceforge.net/projects/acme-crossass>.


O64ml INSTALLATION
==================

0. Download the O64ml tarball and extract its contents, then enter the source
   tree top directory. If you are reading this file, there are chances you
   already did so.


A) QUICK AND (not too) DIRTY:
   --------------------------

   at the shell prompt, type

	./configure -y && make install clean

   O64ml should install with default options.


B) THE NORMAL WAY:
   ---------------

1. Configure the system:

	./configure [OPTIONS]

   Options:
   -b, --bindir <dir>  Directory where the binaries will be installed
   -l, --libdir <dir>  Directory where the O64ml library will be installed
   -m, --mandir <dir>  Directory where the manual pages will be installed
   -p, --prefix <dir>  Same as "-b <dir>/bin -l <dir>/lib/o64ml -m <dir>/man"
   -y, --yes           Assume 'yes' as answer to "install ACME?" prompt
   -h, --help          Show help message and default installation directories

   | NOTE: entering no options will cause the O64ml system to be installed in
   | the current Opam switch (recommended).

2. Build the O64ml system. From the top directory, enter:

	make

3. You can now install the O64ml system. This will copy the o64ml command,
   the stdlib files and the man pages in the directories selected in step 1.
   From the top directory, enter:

	make install

   If the ACME crossassembler is not installed on your system or is obsolete,
   the configuration script will propose to install/upgrade it for you: just
   answer "Y" (no question if you passed the "-y" option to ./configure).
   
   | NOTE: if you ran ./configure with customized directory options, make sure
   | you have the right permissions on target directories. Also ensure than the
   | O64ml final users have the right permissions on all the installed files.
   
   | NOTE: if you have an obsolete ACME version in a directory other than the
   | -b <dir> (or the default binary installation one), ./configure will put
   | the newer ACME release in the latter, leaving the older version in its
   | place; O64ml will use the appropriate one.
   
4. Installation is complete, time to clean up. Enter:

	make clean


UNINSTALLATION
==============

   From the top directory, enter:

	make uninstall

   | NOTE: if you ran ./configure with customized directory options, make sure
   | you have the right permissions on target directories.
 
   | NOTE: if the configuration file ./etc/Makefile.conf is missing, the
   | uninstallation will fail. In that case, re-run ./configure with the same
   | options you entered at installation time, then try to uninstall again.
 
